Interview Questions
1) What is a package in Java, and why do we need it?
-->In Java, a package is a mechanism used to group related classes, interfaces, and sub-packages into a single unit, 
    functioning similarly to a folder in a computer's file system.
    ✅ Why we need it:
    To organize code properly
    To avoid class name conflicts
    To improve maintainability in large projects
    📌 Example: package com.karthikeya.util;


2) Explain the benefits of using packages in Java.
-->✔ Better code organization
    ✔ Avoid naming conflicts
    ✔ Support access control (public, private, protected)
    ✔ Improve reusability
    ✔ Easier maintenance


3) How do packages help in organizing large projects?
-->👉 In large projects:
      
      Code is divided into modules like:
      controller
      service
      repository
      Each module is placed in separate packages
      
      📌 Example structure:
      
      com.project
         ├── controller
         ├── service
         ├── repository
         ├── model
      
      👉 This makes code:
      
      Easy to navigate
      Easy to debug
      Easy to scale


4) Can a class exist without a package? Explain.
-->✅ Yes
    👉 If no package is declared → it belongs to default package
    class Test {
    }

    ⚠️ But:
    Not recommended for large projects
    Cannot be imported by other packages easily



5) Difference between package and import statements.
-->Declaring a package statement after an import statement in Java results in a compile-time error. 
| package                     | import                        |
| --------------------------- | ----------------------------- |
| Defines where class belongs | Used to access other packages |
| Written at top of file      | Written after package         |
| Example: `package com.app;` | `import java.util.Scanner;`   |


6) What is the difference between default package and user-defined packages?
-->: A default package has no name and no declaration statement. A user-defined package has a specific name chosen by the developer.
The main difference between a default package and a user-defined package lies in how they are declared and their level of organization. 

Default Package: This is an "unnamed" package. If you create a Java class without using a package statement at the top of the file,
Java automatically places that class into the default package. It is mainly used for small, simple programs or when you are just beginning 
a project.

User-Defined Package: These are custom packages created by the programmer using the package keyword (e.g., package com.myapp;
| Default Package     | User-defined Package  |
| ------------------- | --------------------- |
| No package declared | Created by programmer |
| Small programs      | Large applications    |
| No structure        | Organized structure   |



7) How do packages improve code reusability and accessibility?
-->👉 Reusability:

    Classes can be reused using import
    
    👉 Accessibility:
    
    Controlled using access modifiers:
    public
    protected
    default
    private
    
    📌 Example:
    
    import com.karthikeya.util.Calculator;


